entry.title: Cleaner fragment count change detection for paint invalidation.
entry.content:
Decouple fragment size and count change detection. Only detect size

changes during layout (and still only if we're fragmented). We can defer

detection of count changes to pre-paint. Doing that reliably in the

middle of layout is impossible, so there were false positives.



No behavior changes intended.



Add a test, to prove that the change in PaintPropertyTreeBuilder::

UpdateFragmentData() is needed.

entry.title: Add histogram to record SQLite errors in AggregationServiceStorageSql
entry.content:
When AggregationServiceStorageSql::DatabaseErrorCallback runs, it will

record the SQLite error in this new histogram, provided that the error

was considered non-fatal.



If this histogram reveals a low volume of "catastrophic" errors related

to disk corruption, we should feel comfortable trashing the database

when we encounter these errors. (See sql::IsErrorCatastrophic().)



Separately, we should investigate whether we can improve the quality of

database error checking in AggregationServiceStorageSql. In particular,

I believe that we should be checking `sql::Statement::is_valid()` before

calling `Run()` or `Step()`. Returning early from functions when the

statement is invalid may prevent knock-on errors from functions that run

two statements in sequence.

entry.title: Improved web native theme update for Aura, Mac and Win
entry.content:
This CL improves how NativeThemeAura, NativeThemeMac and NativeThemeWin

update their web instances. The web native theme is updated via the

ColorSchemeNativeThemeObserver, which notifies the web native theme of

changes to dark mode, high contrast, preferred color scheme and

preferred contrast.



This CL:

1.) Adds a NativeTheme* theme_to_update param in the ctor of the

NativeTheme class

2.) Replaces the existing conditionally heap allocated

color_scheme_observer_ member for each class with a by-value member in

the NativeTheme that observes the system color scheme changes.

3.) Uses of a ScopedObservation member instead of a direct AddObserver

call to manage the lifetime of the observer and avoid dangling pointers

when instances are destroyed.



This change does not introduce any functional changes.

entry.title: [Signin] Fix TriggerListAccounts
entry.content:
Currently in `HandleNextRequest()`, if there is an in progress

/ListAccounts request, any new /ListAccounts request will not be

executed and will be removed from the queue of requests when the current

request completes.



Any cookie changes or calls to `TriggerListAccounts()` will not be

captured if it happens while there is in progress /ListAccounts request.



This CL changes the logic to the following:

- If the next request to be executed is /ListAccounts, remove all other

list accounts in the queue as they should have the same result. They

were triggered before this request starts.

- If the queue contains other requests (set accounts or logout), move

/ListAccounts request to the end of the queue as OAuthMultiLogin and

logout are likely to impact/require a new list accounts request.

entry.title: Suppress LSI updates when adding host_window as widget_ child
entry.content:
Two things are going on with this bug:



1. AddChild involves propagating a non-1 device_scale_factor to

`host_window()` and it triggers `host_window()` to advance its

`LocalSurfaceId`. Changing device_scale_factor this way does not send

configure events.



2. On the first commit, `host_window()->layer()` doesn't have a

`LocalSurfaceId`, and we force it to take `host_window()`'s LSI to

proceed.



As a result, if no configure events are sent after this

device_scale_factor change the `commit_target_layer` cannot be found

b/c neither `old_layer`s nor `host_window()->layer()` has the same

`parent_sequence_number` as `surface_tree_host`'s LSI.



Solution: suppress LSI update when we establish parent-child.



Bug: 1505583

entry.title: [//gpu] Use SharedTextureMemory in DawnIOSurfaceRepresentation
entry.content:
This CL changes DawnIOSurfaceRepresentation from using WrapIOSurface()

to create Dawn textures to using SharedTextureMemory. The advantages of

SharedTextureMemory are:

* It is the forward-looking general-purpose Dawn API for importing

external textures across platforms.

* In the future, we can potentially internally cache Metal textures on a

per-SharedTextureMemory basis and cache SharedTextureMemory objects on

a per-Device basis in the IOSurface image backing. The two things

together would mean that we don't recreate the Metal texture on every

BeginAccess().



While we will be investigating the latter, this CL is just a straight

conversion from using WrapIOSurface() to using SharedTextureMemory.

entry.title: [blink] Change GMBImageCopy::CopyImage() to pass back GMBHandle
entry.content:
As a first step toward converting GpuMemoryBufferImageCopy to use

Mappable SharedImage rather than GpuMemoryBuffer, this CL internalizes

its usage of its GMB by changing its CopyImage() method to pass back a

GMBHandle rather than the GMB. The one caller of this method only uses

the GMB to get the handle.



Note: This CL changes the caller from checking for an error via the

passed in GMB pointer being null to checking for the error via

GMBHandle::is_null() being true. This check is semantically equivalent

because the GMB is created via

ClientGMBManager::CreateGpuMemoryBuffer(), which returns nullptr if

is_null() returns true on the backing handle [1]; hence, when the

GMBImageCopy's GMB is non-null, is_null() is guaranteed to be false on

its backing handle (and when GMBImageCopy's GMB *is* null, we pass a

GMBHandle for which is_null() will be true).



[1] https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:services/viz/public/cpp/gpu/client_gpu_memory_buffer_manager.cc;l=169-170;drc=8e78783dc1f7007bad46d657c9f332614e240fd8;bpv=1;bpt=1

entry.title: [editing] Fix triple-clicking a contenteditable next to a non-contenteditable doesn't select the whole paragraph
entry.content:
Consider this test case:



Paragraph 1




Paragraph 2








Triple-clicking div#one which is next to a non-contenteditable element,

`new_selection` is returned by `ExpandWithGranularity`.

The value `new_selection.Extent()` is `div#two@offsetInAnchor[0]`.

Since div#two is non-editable, `VisiblePosition` of

`new_selection.Extent()` is null.

`CanonicalizeSelection` return a caret selection. In this case,

triple-clicking from the user's perspective will not select anything.



`AdjustSelectionToAvoidCrossingEditingBoundaries` ensures selection

not crossing editing boundaries, but `AdjustSelectionType` returned

the wrong result. It will call `MostForward/BackwardCaretPosition`

on `Extent/Base`, this will result in the `VisiblePosition` of

the selection will be the caret. In this case, we shouldn't

forward/backward the start/end position of `range`.



Bug: 1371268
